	<fdd:identificationAndDescription>
		<fdd:fullName>AVI OpenDML with Motion JPEG Video </fdd:fullName>
		<fdd:keywords>
			<fdd:keyword>video formats</fdd:keyword>
			<fdd:keyword>AVI</fdd:keyword>
			<fdd:keyword>Motion JPEG</fdd:keyword>
			<fdd:keyword>OpenDML</fdd:keyword>
		</fdd:keywords>
		<fdd:description>File format that wraps a series of JPEG images with other data chunks, e.g., audio, in <fddLink id="fdd000442">AVI_OpenDML_1_02</fddLink>, to produce a moving image sequence, referred to as <i>Motion JPEG</i> (MJPEG). The images represent individual frames (or fields? <a href="../contact_format.shtml">Comments welcome</a>) from a pre-existing video recording, generally analog.  The images employ a form of the <fddLink id="fdd000017">JPEG</fddLink> still image compression algorithm, as specified by <fddLink id="fdd000442">AVI_OpenDML_1_02</fddLink>.  Microsoft refers to this encoding as <i>JPEG DIB</i> (Device Independent Bitmap).  See <a href="#notes">Notes</a> for more information.</fdd:description>
		<fdd:shortDescription>File format that wraps a series of JPEG images with other data chunks, e.g., audio, in AVI_OpenDML_1_02, to produce a moving image sequence, referred to as Motion JPEG (MJPEG).</fdd:shortDescription>
		<fdd:productionPhase>Generally a middle-state or final-state format.</fdd:productionPhase>
